ce-3/"},{"index":"6","term":"Authentication","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The process by which an entity (such as a person or computer system) determines whether another entity is who it claims to be.","new_definition":"The process by which an entity (such as a person or computer system) determines whether another entity is who it claims to be.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"23","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/authentication/"},{"index":"7","term":"Automated Processing","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"A processing operation that is performed without any human intervention.","new_definition":"A processing operation performed without any human intervention.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"8","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/automated-processing/"},{"index":"8","term":"Behavioral Advertising","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"Behavioral Ads","definition":"Advertising that is targeted at individuals based on the observation of their behavior over time. Most often done via automated processing of personal data or profiling.","new_definition":"Advertising targeted at individuals based on the observation of their behavior over time. Most often done via automated processing of personal data or profiling.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"24","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/behavioral-advertising-2/"},{"index":"9","term":"Big Data","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"A term used to describe the large data sets that exponential growth in the amount and availability of data have allowed organizations to collect. Big data has been articulated as “the three V’s: volume (the amount of data), velocity (the speed at which data may now be collected and analyzed), and variety (the format, structured or unstructured, and type of data -- for example, transactional or behavioral).","new_definition":"Large data sets that have become feasible to create because of an exponential growth in the amount and availability of data. Big data is defined by “the three Vs\": volume (the amount of data), velocity (the speed at which data may now be collected and analyzed), and variety (the format and type of data -- for example, transactional or behavioral).","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"60","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/big-data/"},{"index":"10","term":"Biometrics","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"Data concerning the intrinsic physical or behavioral characteristics of an individual. Examples include DNA, fingerprints, retina and iris patterns, voice, face, handwriting, keystroke technique and gait.","new_definition":"Data concerning the intrinsic physical or behavioral characteristics of an individual. Examples include DNA, fingerprints, retina and iris patterns, voice, face, handwriting, keystroke technique and gait.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"26","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/biometrics/"},{"index":"11","term":"Breach Notification","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"Breach Notifications","definition":"The requirement that an organization notify regulators and/or victims of incidents affecting the confidentiality and security of personal data. The requirements in this arena vary wildly by jurisdiction. It is a transparency mechanism that highlights operational failures, which helps mitigate damage and aids in the understanding of causes of failure.","new_definition":"The requirement that an organization notify regulators and/or victims when the confidentiality and security of personal data has been compromised. This transparency mechanism helps mitigate damage and aids in determining the cause of the breach.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"35","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/breach-disclosure/"},{"index":"12","term":"Bring Your Own Device","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"Use of employees’ own personal computing devices for work purposes.","new_definition":"Use of employees’ own personal computing devices for work purposes.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"10","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/bring-your-own-device/"},{"index":"13","term":"California Consumer Privacy Act","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The first state-level comprehensive privacy law in the United States. The C.C.P.A., which comes into force in 2020, will apply broadly to businesses that collect personal information from California consumers, imposing extensive transparency and disclosure obligations. It also creates consumers’ rights to see their personal data and to request its deletion; to opt out of the sale of their personal data; and to nondiscrimination on the basis of their exercising their C.C.P.A. rights.","new_definition":"The first state-level online privacy law in the United States.The law will give consumers more control and insight into the ways their personal data is used by companies. Consumers will have the right to see their personal data, request its deletion, opt out of its sale, and the right to equal services regardless of whether they exercise their rights under the law.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"62","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/california-consumer-privacy-act-2/"},{"index":"15","term":"Chief Privacy Officer","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"Chief Privacy Officers","definition":"A position within an organization that is responsible for managing risks of privacy laws and policies.","new_definition":"A position within an organization responsible for managing risks of privacy laws and policies.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"14","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/chief-privacy-officer-agency-level/"},{"index":"16","term":"Children's Online Privacy Protection Act","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"A federal law that applies to the operators of commercial websites and online services that are directed to children under the age of 13. It also applies to general audience websites and online services that have actual knowledge that they are collecting personal information from children under the age of 13. The act requires these website operators to post a privacy notice on the homepage of the website; provide notice about collection practices to parents; obtain verifiable parental consent before collecting personal information from children; give parents a choice as to whether their child’s personal information will be disclosed to third parties; provide parents access and the opportunity to delete the child’s personal information and opt out of future collection or use of the information; and maintain the confidentiality, security and integrity of personal information collected from children.","new_definition":"A federal law that requires companies to obtain explicit, verifiable permission from parents before collecting, using or disclosing personal information from children under 13 or targeting them with behavioral ads.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"30","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/childrens-online-privacy-protection-act-of-2000-the/"},{"index":"17","term":"Cloud Computing","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The provision of information technology services over the Internet. These services may be provided by a company for its internal users in a \"private cloud\" or by third-party suppliers. The services can include software, infrastructure (like servers), hosting and platforms (like operating systems). Cloud computing has numerous applications, from personal webmail to corporate data storage, and can be subdivided into different types of service models.","new_definition":"Computing power provided over the Internet. Cloud computing has numerous service models and applications, from personal webmail to corporate data storage.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"21","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/cloud-computing/"},{"index":"18","term":"Consent","hide_tooltip":"x","secondary_terms":"","definition":"This privacy requirement is one of the fair information practices. Individuals must be able to prevent the collection of their personal data, unless the disclosure is required by law. If an individual has choice about the use or disclosure of his or her information, consent is the individual's way of giving permission for the use or disclosure. Consent may be affirmative (\"opt in\") or implied (that is, the individual didn’t opt out).\n(1) Affirmative/Explicit Consent: A requirement that an individual \"signifies\" his or her agreement with a data controller by some active communication between the parties. \n\n(2) Implicit Consent: Implied consent arises where consent may reasonably be inferred from the action or inaction of the individual.","new_definition":"An individual's way of giving permission for the use or disclosure of information. Affirmative consent means the individual actively opted in. Implied consent means the individual did not opt out.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"30","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/consent-2/"},{"index":"19","term":"Consumer Financial Protection Bureau","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"Created by the Dodd-Frank Act, the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau is intended to consolidate the oversight of the financial industry. It is an independent bureau within the Federal Reserve and when it was created took rule-making authority over Fair Credit and Reporting Act and Gramm-Leach-Billey Act regulations from the Federal Trade Commission and financial industry regulators. Its enforcement powers include authority to take action against “abusive acts and practices” as specified by the Dodd-Frank Act.","new_definition":"A government agency created to consolidate oversight of the financial industry. It has the authority to take action against “abusive acts and practices” as specified by the Dodd-Frank Act.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"29","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/consumer-financial-protection-bureau/"},{"index":"20","term":"Cookie","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"Cookies","definition":"A small text file stored on a client machine that may later be retrieved by a web server from the machine. Cookies allow web servers to keep track of the end user’s browser activities, and connect individual web requests into a session. Cookies allow users to see multiple password-protected pages during a session by recording that the users have supplied their username and password already. Cookies may be referred to as \"first party\" (if they are placed by the website that is visited) or \"third party\" (if they are placed by a party other than the visited website). Additionally, they may be referred to as \"session cookies\" if they are deleted when a session ends, or \"persistent cookies\" if they remain longer.","new_definition":"A small file stored by a website on computers that allows companies to track browser activity, remember user preferences and keep users logged in for subsequent sessions. First-party cookies are placed by the website that is visited, while third-party cookies are placed by a party other than the visited website.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"50","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/cookie/"},{"index":"21","term":"Court of Justice of the European Union","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The Court of Justice is the judicial body of the European Union that makes decisions on issues of E.U. law and enforces European decisions either in respect to actions taken by the European Commission against a member state or actions taken by individuals to enforce their rights under E.U. law. Based in Luxembourg, the court was set up in 1951, and was originally named the Court of Justice of the European Communities. The court is frequently confused with the European Court of Human Rights, which oversees human rights laws across Europe, including in many non-E.U. countries, and is not linked to the E.U. institutions.","new_definition":"The judicial body of the European Union that decides issues of E.U. law and enforces decisions.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"16","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/court-of-justice-of-the-european-union/"},{"index":"22","term":"Cross-Border Data Transfers","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The transmission of personal information from one jurisdiction to another. Many jurisdictions, most notably the European Union, place significant restrictions on such transfers. The E.U. requires that the receiving jurisdiction be judged to have “adequate” data protection practices.","new_definition":"The transmission of personal information from one jurisdiction to another. Many jurisdictions, notably the E.U., place significant restrictions on these transfers.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"21","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/cross-border-data-transfers/"},{"index":"23","term":"Data Breach","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"Data Breaches","definition":"The unauthorized acquisition of computerized data that compromises the security, confidentiality or integrity of personal information maintained by a data collector. Breaches do not include good-faith acquisitions of personal information by an employee or agent of the data collector for a legitimate purpose of the data collector — provided the personal information is not used for a purpose unrelated to the data collector's business or subject to further unauthorized disclosure","new_definition":"The unauthorized acquisition of data that compromises the security, confidentiality or integrity of personal information maintained by a data collector.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"20","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/data-breach/"},{"index":"24","term":"Data Broker","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"Data Brokers","definition":"Entities that collect, aggregate and sell individuals’ personal data, derivatives and inferences from disparate public and private sources.","new_definition":"Entities that collect, aggregate and sell individuals’ personal data, derivatives and inferences from disparate public and private sources.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"18","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/data-brokers/"},{"index":"25","term":"Data Controller","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"Data Controllers","definition":"The natural or legal person, public authority, agency or any other body that determines the purposes and means of the processing of personal data. Where the purposes and means of such processing are determined by European Union or member state law, the controller or the specific criteria for its nomination may be provided for by E.U. or member state law.","new_definition":"The people, authorities, agencies or other bodies that determine how and why personal data is permitted.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"16","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/data-controller/"},{"index":"26","term":"Data Minimization Principle","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The idea that one should only collect and retain that personal data which is necessary.","new_definition":"The idea that one should only collect and retain personal data that is necessary.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"14","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/data-minimization-principle/"},{"index":"27","term":"Data Portability","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The notion that in certain circumstances, generally where data processing is done on the basis of consent or a contract, data subjects have the right to receive their personal data, which they have provided to a controller, in a structured, commonly used and machine-readable format and have the right to transmit that data to another controller without hindrance from the controller to which the personal data has been provided.","new_definition":"The idea that in certain circumstances, people have the right to receive a copy of their personal data from one entity and transfer that data to another entity.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"28","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/data-portability/"},{"index":"28","term":"Data Processing","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"Any operation or set of operations that is performed on personal data or on sets of personal data, whether or not by automated means, such as collection, recording, organization, structuring, storage, adaptation or alteration, retrieval, consultation, use, disclosure by transmission, dissemination or otherwise making available, alignment or combination, restriction, erasure or destruction.","new_definition":"Any operation performed on personal data, including collection, recording, organization, structuring, storage, adaptation or alteration, retrieval, consultation, use, disclosure by transmission, erasure and destruction.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"24","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/data-processing/"},{"index":"32","term":"Data Protection","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The rules and safeguards applying under various laws and regulations to personal data about individuals that organizations collect, store, use and disclose. “Data protection” is the professional term used in the European Union, whereas in the United States the concept is generally referred to as “information privacy.” Data protection is different from data security, since it extends beyond securing information to devising and instituting policies for its fair use.","new_definition":"The rules applying under various laws and regulations to personal data that organizations collect, store, use and disclose. “Data protection” is the professional term used in the European Union, whereas in the United States, the concept is generally referred to as “information privacy.” This is different from data security, since it extends beyond securing information to devising and instituting policies for its fair use.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"64","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/data-protection/"},{"index":"29","term":"Data Protection Authority","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"Data Protection Authorities","definition":"Independent public authorities that supervise the application of data protection laws in the E.U. They provide advice on data protection issues and field complaints from individuals alleging violations of the General Data Protection Regulation. Each E.U. member state has its own data protection authority. Under the General Data Protection Regulation,  the authorities have extensive enforcement powers, including the ability to impose fines that total 4 percent of a company’s global annual revenue.","new_definition":"Independent public authorities that supervise the application of data protection laws in the European Union. They provide advice on data protection issues and field complaints from individuals alleging violations of the General Data Protection Regulation. Each E.U. member state has its own data protection authority. Under the General Data Protection Regulation,  the authorities have extensive enforcement powers, including the ability to impose fines that total 4 percent of a company’s global annual revenue.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"73","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/data-protection-authority-eu-specific/"},{"index":"30","term":"Data Protection by Design","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"When developing, designing, selecting and using applications, services and products that are based on the processing of personal data or process personal data to fulfill their task, producers of the products, services and applications should be encouraged to take into account the right to data protection when developing and designing such products, services and applications and, with due regard to the state of the art, to make sure that controllers and processors are able to fulfill their data protection obligations.","new_definition":"An approach to designing any application, service or product that considers the right to data protection.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"16","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/data-protection-by-design/"},{"index":"31","term":"Data Protection Officer","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"Data Protection Officers","definition":"While the title of data protection officer has long been in use, particularly in Germany and France, the General Data Protection Regulation introduced a new legal definition with specific tasks. Certain organizations, particularly those that process personal data as part of their business model or those who process special categories of data are obligated to designate a data protection officer based on professional qualities and, in particular, expert knowledge of data protection law and practices.","new_definition":"Under the General Data Protection Regulation, certain organizations are obligated to designate an officer who is responsible for ensuring compliance with data protection laws.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"24","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/data-protection-officer/"},{"index":"33","term":"Data Subject","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"Data Subjects","definition":"An identified or identifiable natural person.","new_definition":"An identified or identifiable natural person.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"6","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/data-subject/"},{"index":"34","term":"De-identification","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"An action taken to remove identifying characteristics from data.","new_definition":"An action taken to remove identifying characteristics from data.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"9","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/280017/"},{"index":"35","term":"Digital Fingerprinting","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The use of log files to identify a website visitor. It is often used for security and system maintenance purposes. Log files generally include the IP address of the visitor; a time stamp; the URL of the requested page or file; a referrer URL; and the visitor’s web browser, operating system and font preferences. In some cases, combining this information can be used to “fingerprint” a device. This more detailed information varies enough among computing devices that two devices are unlikely to be the same. It is used as a security technique by financial institutions and others initiating additional security assurances before allowing users to log on from a new device. Some privacy enforcement agencies; however, have questioned what would constitute sufficient notice and consent for digital fingerprinting techniques to be used for targeted advertising.","new_definition":"The use of log files to identify a website visitor. It is often used for security and system maintenance purposes. Log files generally include the IP address of the visitor; a time stamp; the URL of the requested page or file; a referrer URL; and the visitor’s web browser, operating system and font preferences. In some cases, combining this information can be used to “fingerprint” a device.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"67","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/third-party-collection/"},{"index":"36","term":"E.U.-U.S. Privacy Shield","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"Created in 2016 to replace the invalidated Safe Harbor agreement, the Privacy Shield is an adequacy agreement that allows for the transfer of personal data from the E.U. to the United States for companies participating in the program. Only those companies that fall under the jurisdiction of the Federal Trade Commission may certify to the Shield principles and participate, which notably excludes health care, financial services and nonprofit institutions.","new_definition":"Created in 2016 to replace the invalidated  Safe Harbor agreement, the Privacy Shield is an adequacy agreement that allows for the transfer of personal data from the E.U. to the United States for companies participating in the program. Only those companies that fall under the jurisdiction of the Federal Trade Commission may certify to the Shield principles and participate, which notably excludes health care, financial services and nonprofit institutions.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"69","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/eu-us-privacy-shield/"},{"index":"37","term":"Encryption","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The process of obscuring information, often through the use of a cryptographic scheme, in order to make the information unreadable without special knowledge, as in the use of code keys. Encryption is mentioned in the General Data Protection Regulation as a potential way to mitigate risk, and certain breach notification requirements may be mitigated by the use of encryption as it reduces the risks to the rights and freedoms of data subjects should data be improperly disclosed.","new_definition":"The process of obscuring information, often through the use of a cryptographic scheme, in order to make the information unreadable without special knowledge.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"23","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/encryption/"},{"index":"38","term":"ePrivacy Directive","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"ePrivacy Directives","definition":"A sectoral privacy directive for European Union member states that applies to the digital industry. Among other provisions, the ePrivacy Directive requires websites to obtain consumer consent before placing cookies for marketing purposes. The E.U. is considering reform of the ePrivacy Directive.","new_definition":"A privacy directive for European Union Member States, which applies to the digital industry. Among other provisions, the ePrivacy Directive requires websites to obtain consent before placing cookies for marketing purposes. The E.U. is considering changing the directive.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"38","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/eprivacy-directive-2/"},{"index":"39","term":"European Data Protection Board","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"An independent public authority responsible for monitoring the application of the General Data Protection Regulation in order to protect the fundamental rights and freedoms of natural persons in relation to processing and to facilitate the free flow of personal data within the European Union.","new_definition":"An independent public authority responsible for monitoring the application of the General Data Protection Regulation in order to protect the fundamental rights and freedoms of natural persons in relation to processing and to facilitate the free flow of personal data within the E.U.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"43","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/european-data-protection-board-2/"},{"index":"40","term":"Fair Credit Reporting Act","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"One of the oldest federal privacy laws still in force today. It was enacted in 1970 to mandate accurate and relevant data collection, give consumers the ability to see and correct their information, and limit the use of consumer reports to permissible purposes, such as employment and extension of credit or insurance.","new_definition":"One of the oldest federal privacy laws still in force today. It was enacted in 1970 to mandate accurate and relevant data collection, give consumers the ability to see and correct their information, and limit the use of consumer reports to purposes like employment and extension of credit or insurance.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"50","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/fair-credit-reporting-act/"},{"index":"41","term":"Fair Information Practice Principles","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"(1) The Collection Limitation Principle.  There should be limits to the collection of personal data and any such data should be obtained by lawful and fair means and, where appropriate, with the knowledge or consent of the data subject.\n (2) The Data Quality Principle. Personal data should be relevant to the purposes for which they are to be used and, to the extent necessary for those purposes, should be accurate, complete and kept up-to-date. \n(3) The Purpose Specification Principle. The purposes for which personal data are collected should be specified not later than at the time of data collection and the subsequent use limited to the fulfillment of those purposes or such others as are not incompatible with those purposes and as are specified on each occasion of change of purpose. \n(4) The Use Limitation Principle. Personal data should not be disclosed, made available or otherwise used for purposes other than those specified, except a) with the consent of the data subject, or b) by the authority of law. \n(5) The Security Safeguards Principle. Personal data should be protected by reasonable security safeguards against such risks as loss or unauthorized access, destruction, use, modification or disclosure of data. \n(6) The Openness Principle. There should be a general policy of openness about developments, practices and policies with respect to personal data. Means should be readily available of establishing the existence and nature of personal data and the main purposes of their use, as well as the identity and usual residence of the data controller. \n(7) The Individual Participation Principle. An individual should have the right: \na) to obtain from a data controller, or otherwise, confirmation of whether or not the data controller has data relating to him; \nb) to have data relating to him communicated to him, within a reasonable time, at a charge, if any, that is not excessive; in a reasonable manner, and in a form that is readily intelligible to him; \nc) to be given reasons if a request made under subparagraphs (a) and (b) is denied and to be able to challenge such denial; and \nd) to challenge data relating to him and, if the challenge is successful, to have the data erased, rectified, completed or amended; \n(8) The Accountability Principle. A data controller should be accountable for complying with measures which give effect to the principles stated above.\n","new_definition":"A set of unenforced principles set forth by the Federal Trade Commission for collecting data in a consumer-privacy-friendly manner. The principles recommend that personal data collection be limited, relevant, specified and reasonably secured. The principles also advocate an individual's right to see personal data and the right to have data deleted or amended.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"53","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/fair-information-practices/"},{"index":"42","term":"Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"A law that establishes requirements regarding the privacy protection of student educational records. It applies to all academic institutions that receive funds under applicable Department of Education programs. The law gives parents certain rights with respect to their children’s education records. These rights transfer to the student when he or she reaches the age of 18 or attends a school beyond the high school level. Students to whom the rights have transferred are referred to as “eligible students.”","new_definition":"A law that establishes requirements regarding the privacy protection of student educational records. It applies to all academic institutions that receive funds under applicable . Department of Education programs. The law gives parents and eligible students certain rights with respect to the student's education records.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"45","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/family-educational-rights-and-privacy-act-2/"},{"index":"43","term":"Federal Trade Commission","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The United States' primary consumer protection agency, the F.T.C. collects complaints about companies, business practices and identity theft under the F.T.C. Act and other laws. The F.T.C. brings actions under Section 5 of the F.T.C. Act, which prohibits unfair and deceptive trade practices.","new_definition":"The United States' primary consumer protection agency, the F.T.C. collects complaints about companies, business practices and identity theft under the F.T.C. Act and other laws. The agency brings actions under Section 5 of the F.T.C. Act, which prohibits unfair and deceptive trade practices.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"43","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/federal-trade-commission-2/"},{"index":"44","term":"First-Party Data","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"Data collected directly from individuals.","new_definition":"Data collected directly from individuals.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"5","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/third-party-collection/"},{"index":"14","term":"General Data Protection Regulation","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The General Data Protection Regulation replaced the Data Protection Directive in 2018. The aim of the regulation is to provide one set of data protection rules for all E.U. member states and the European Economic Area. ","new_definition":"The General Data Protection Regulation replaced the Data Protection Directive in 2018. Its aim is to provide one set of data protection rules for all E.U. member states and the European Economic Area.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"33","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/general-data-protection-regulation/#"},{"index":"45","term":"Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The commonly used name for the Financial Services Modernization Act of 1999. The act re-organized financial services regulation in the United States and applies broadly to any company that is “significantly engaged” in financial activities. In its privacy provisions, the act addresses the handling of non-public personal information, defined broadly to include a consumer’s name and address, and consumers’ interactions with banks, insurers and other financial institutions. The act requires financial institutions to securely store personal financial information, give notice of their policies regarding the sharing of personal financial information, and give consumers the ability to opt out of some sharing of personal financial information.","new_definition":"The commonly used name for the Financial Services Modernization Act of 1999. It requires financial institutions to securely store personal financial information, give notice of their policies regarding the sharing of personal financial information, and give consumers the ability to opt out of some sharing of personal financial information.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"49","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/gramm-leach-bliley-act/"},{"index":"46","term":"Health Information Technology for Economic and Clinical Health Act","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"Enacted as part of the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009, the act, further addresses privacy and security issues involving personal health information as defined by the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act. Its privacy provisions include the introduction of categories of violations based on culpability that, in turn, are tied to tiered ranges of civil monetary penalties. Its most noteworthy elements elaborate upon breach notifications resulting from the use or disclosure of information that compromises its security or privacy.","new_definition":"Enacted in 2009, the act introduced monetary penalties for failing to protect the privacy and security of personal health information as defined by the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"30","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/health-information-technology-for-economic-and-clinical-health-act-the/"},{"index":"47","term":"Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"A federal law to create national standards for electronic health care transactions. It required the Department of Health and Human Services to promulgate regulations to protect the privacy and security of personal health information. The basic rule is that patients have to opt in before their information can be shared with other organizations,  although there are important exceptions for treatment, payment and health care operations.","new_definition":"A federal law to create national standards for electronic healthcare transactions. The basic rule is that patients have to opt in before their information can be shared with other organizations, although there are exceptions such for treatment, payment and health care operations.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"42","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act-the/"},{"index":"48","term":"Information Privacy","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The claim of individuals, groups or institutions to determine for themselves when, how and to what extent information about them is communicated to others.","new_definition":"The claim of individuals, groups or institutions to determine for themselves when, how and to what extent information about them is communicated to others.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"24","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/information-privacy/"},{"index":"49","term":"Information Security","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The protection of information for the purposes of preventing loss, unauthorized access and misuse. It is also the process of assessing threats and risks to information and the procedures and controls to preserve confidentiality, integrity and availability of information.","new_definition":"The protection of information for the purposes of preventing loss, unauthorized access and misuse. It is also the process of assessing threats and risks to information and the procedures and controls to preserve confidentiality, integrity and availability of information.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"39","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/information-security/"},{"index":"50","term":"Location Data","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"Data indicating the geographical position of a device, including data relating to its latitude, longitude and altitude, the direction of travel of the use and the time the location information was recorded.","new_definition":"Data indicating the geographical position of a device, including data relating to its latitude, longitude and altitude, the direction of travel of the use and the time the location information was recorded. ","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"32","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/location-data/"},{"index":"51","term":"Machine Learning","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"A subfield of, or building block for, artificial intelligence, machine learning is a problem-solving technique that trains a computer to identify new patterns. It uses various algorithms in a problem-solving process that includes data cleansing, feature selection, training, testing and validation. Companies and government agencies increasingly deploy machine learning algorithms for tasks such as fraud detection, speech recognition, image classification and other pattern-recognition applications.","new_definition":"A subfield of artificial intelligence, machine learning is a problem-solving technique that trains a computer to identify new patterns. It uses various algorithms in a problem-solving process that includes data cleansing, feature selection, training, testing, and validation. Companies and government agencies increasingly deploy machine learning algorithms for tasks such as fraud detection, speech recognition and image classification.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"57","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/machine-learning/"},{"index":"52","term":"One-Stop Shop","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"One-Stop Shops","definition":"A colloquial description of the E.U.’s General Data Protection Regulation’s consistency mechanism that allows a specific data protection authority to function as a business’s single point of contact or lead supervisory authority for a complaint or investigation. This saves businesses from the need to potentially engage with the various authorities from the 28 E.U. member states.","new_definition":"A colloquial description of the E.U.’s General Data Protection Regulation’s consistency mechanism that allows a specific data protection authority to function as a business’s single point of contact or lead supervisory authority for a complaint or investigation.This saves businesses from the need to potentially engage with the various authorities from the 28 E.U. member states.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"55","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/one-stop-shop/"},{"index":"53","term":"Opt In","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"One of two central concepts of choice (the other is opt out). It means an individual makes an active affirmative indication of choice by, for example, checking a box signaling a desire to share his or her information with third parties.","new_definition":"One of two central concepts of choice (the other is opt out). It means an individual makes an active affirmative indication of choice by, for example, checking a box signaling a desire to share his or her information with third parties.\n","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"41","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/opt-in/"},{"index":"54","term":"Opt Out","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"One of two central concepts of choice (the other, opt in). It means an individual’s lack of action implies that a choice has been made; unless,  say, an individual checks or unchecks a box, his or her information will be shared with third parties.","new_definition":"One of two central concepts of choice (the other, opt in). It means an individual’s lack of action implies that a choice has been made; unless,  say, an individual checks or unchecks a box, his or her information will be shared with third parties.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"44","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/opt-out/"},{"index":"55","term":"Passive Data Collection","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"Data collection in which information is gathered automatically, often without the end user’s knowledge, as the user navigates from page to page on a website. This is typically accomplished through the use of cookies, web beacons or other types of identification mechanisms.","new_definition":"Data collection in which information is gathered automatically, often without the end user’s knowledge, as the user navigates from page to page on a website. This is typically accomplished through the use of cookies, web beacons or other types of identification mechanisms.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"42","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/passive-data-collection/"},{"index":"56","term":"Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"A self-regulatory system that provides an enforceable security standard for payment card data. The rules were drafted by the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council, which built on previous rules written by the various credit card companies. Except for small companies, compliance with the standard requires hiring a third party to conduct security assessments and detect violations. Failure to comply can lead to exclusion from Visa, MasterCard or other major payment card systems, as well as penalties.","new_definition":"A self-regulatory system that provides an enforceable security standard for payment card data. The rules were drafted by the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council, which built on previous rules written by the various credit card companies. ","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"37","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/pci-data-security-standard/"},{"index":"57","term":"Personal Data","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The predominant term for personal information in the European Union, defined broadly in the General Data Protection Regulation as any information relating to an identified or identifiable natural person.","new_definition":"The common term for personal information in the European Union, defined broadly in the General Data Protection Regulation as any information relating to an identified or identifiable natural person.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"29","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/personal-data-eu-specific/"},{"index":"58","term":"Personal Information","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"A synonym for \"personal data.\" It is a term with particular meaning under the California Consumer Privacy Act, which defines it as information that identifies, relates to, describes, is capable of being associated with, or could reasonably be linked, directly or indirectly, with a particular consumer.","new_definition":"A synonym for \"personal data.\" It is a term with particular meaning under the California Consumer Privacy Act, which defines it as information that identifies, relates to, describes, is capable of being associated with, or could reasonably be linked, directly or indirectly, with a particular consumer.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"46","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/personal-information/"},{"index":"59","term":"Personally Identifiable Information","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"Any information about an individual, including any information that can be used to distinguish or trace an individual’s identity, such as name, Social Security number, date and place of birth, mother’s maiden name or biometric records; and any other information that is linkable to an individual, such as medical, educational, financial and employment information.","new_definition":"Any information about an individual, including any information that can be used to distinguish or trace an individual’s identity, such as name, Social Security number, date and place of birth, mother’s maiden name or biometric records; and any other information that is linkable to an individual, such as medical, educational, financial and employment information.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"54","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/personally-identifiable-information/"},{"index":"60","term":"Pre-emption","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"A superior government’s ability to have its laws supersede those of an inferior government. For example, the  federal government has mandated that no state government can regulate consumer credit reporting.","new_definition":"A superior government’s ability to have its laws supersede those of an inferior government. For example, the federal government has mandated that no state government can regulate consumer credit reporting.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"30","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/preemption/"},{"index":"61","term":"Privacy by Design","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"Generally regarded as a synonym for data protection by design. However, privacy by design as a specific term was first outlined in a framework in the mid-1990s by the information and privacy commissioner of Ontario, Canada, Ann Cavoukian, with seven foundational principles.","new_definition":"Generally regarded as a synonym for data protection by design. However, privacy by design as a specific term was first outlined in a framework in the mid-1990s by the information and privacy commissioner of Ontario, Canada, Ann Cavoukian, with seven foundational principles.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"42","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/privacy-by-design/"},{"index":"62","term":"Privacy Policy","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"Privacy Policies","definition":"An internal statement that governs an organization or entity’s handling of personal information. It is directed at those members of the organization who might handle or make decisions regarding the personal information, instructing them on the collection, use, storage and destruction of the data, as well as any specific rights the data subjects may have. May also be referred to as a data protection policy.","new_definition":"A statement that governs an organization or entity’s handling of personal information. It is directed at those members of the organization who might handle or make decisions regarding the personal information, instructing them on the collection, use, storage and destruction of the data, as well as any specific rights the data subjects may have. May also be referred to as a data protection policy.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"64","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/privacy-policy/"},{"index":"63","term":"Private Right of Action","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"Unless otherwise restricted by law, any individual who is harmed by a violation of the law can file a lawsuit against the violator.","new_definition":"Unless otherwise restricted by law, any individual who is harmed by a violation of the law can file a lawsuit against the violator.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"23","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/private-right-of-action/"},{"index":"64","term":"Profiling","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"Any form of automated processing of personal data consisting of the use of personal data to evaluate certain personal aspects, in particular to analyze or predict aspects concerning that person's performance at work, economic situation, health, personal preferences, interests, reliability, behavior, location or movements.","new_definition":"Any form of automated processing of personal data consisting of the use of personal data to evaluate certain personal aspects, in particular to analyze or predict aspects concerning that person's performance at work, economic situation, health, personal preferences, interests, reliability, behavior, location or movements.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"44","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/profiling/"},{"index":"65","term":"Protected Health Information","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"Any individually identifiable health information transmitted or maintained in any form or medium that is held by an entity covered by the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act or its business associate; identifies the individual or offers a reasonable basis for identification; is created or received by a covered entity or an employer; and relates to a past, present or future physical or mental condition, provision of health care or payment for health care to that individual.","new_definition":"Any individually identifiable health information transmitted or maintained by an entity covered by the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"20","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/protected-health-information/"},{"index":"66","term":"Pseudonymization","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The processing of personal data in such a manner that the personal data can no longer be attributed to a specific data subject without the use of additional information, provided that such additional information is kept separately and is subject to technical and organizational measures to ensure that the personal data are not attributed to an identified or identifiable natural person.","new_definition":"The processing of personal data in such a manner that the personal data can no longer be attributed to an individual without the use of additional information.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"27","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/pseudonymisation/"},{"index":"67","term":"Re-identification","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The action of reattaching identifying characteristics to pseudonymized or de-identified data. Often invoked as a “risk of re-identification” or “re-identification risk,” which refers to nullifying the de-identification actions previously applied to data.","new_definition":"The action of reattaching identifying characteristics to pseudonymized or de-identified data. Often invoked as a “risk of re-identification” or “re-identification risk,” which refers to nullifying the de-identification actions previously applied to data.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"32","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/reidentification-2/"},{"index":"68","term":"Red Flags Rule","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"A regulation created by the Federal Trade Commission under the authority of the Fair and Accurate Credit Transactions Act of 2003. This regulation requires financial institutions and creditors to institute measures to detect and prevent identity theft.","new_definition":"A regulation created by the Federal Trade Commission under the authority of the Fair and Accurate Credit Transactions Act of 2003. This regulation requires financial institutions and creditors to institute measures to detect and prevent identity theft.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"37","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/red-flags-rule/"},{"index":"69","term":"Retargeting","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"A type of online advertising in which visitors to a website are targeted with ads related to that website as they browse elsewhere. The most common form of retargeting is a digital advertising network, which displays advertisements to a user related to a website previously visited by the user across all third-party websites in a network.","new_definition":"A type of online advertising where visitors to a website are targeted with ads related to that website as they browse elsewhere. The most common form of retargeting is a digital advertising network, which displays advertisements to a user related to a website previously visited by the user across all third-party websites in a network.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"55","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/third-party-collection/"},{"index":"70","term":"Right of Access","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"An individual’s right to request and receive personal data from a business or other organization.","new_definition":"An individual’s right to request and receive personal data from a business or other organization.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"15","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/right-of-access/"},{"index":"71","term":"Right to Be Forgotten","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"An individual’s right to have personal data deleted by a business or other organization possessing or controlling that data.","new_definition":"An individual’s right to have personal data deleted by a business or other organization possessing or controlling that data.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"19","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/right-to-be-forgotten/"},{"index":"72","term":"Right to Deletion","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"An individual’s right to have personal data deleted by a business or other organization possessing or controlling that data.","new_definition":"An individual’s right to have personal data deleted by a business or other organization possessing or controlling that data.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"19","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/right-to-deletion/"},{"index":"73","term":"Right to No Sale","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"An individual’s right to prohibit or restrict the transfer of information for value from a business to a third party.","new_definition":"An individual’s right to prohibit or restrict the transfer of information for value from a business to a third party.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"20","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/right-to-no-sale/"},{"index":"74","term":"Right to Object","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"An individual’s right to object to the processing of personal data by a business or other organization. An entity is obligated to review an individual’s objection and respond to it.","new_definition":"An individual’s right to object to the processing of personal data by a business or other organization. An entity is obligated to review an individual’s objection and respond to it.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"30","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/right-to-object-2/"},{"index":"75","term":"Right to Rectification","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"An individual’s right to have personal data corrected or amended by a business or other organization if it is inaccurate.","new_definition":"An individual’s right to have personal data corrected or amended by a business or other organization if it is inaccurate.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"20","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/rectification-2/"},{"index":"76","term":"Right to Restriction of Processing","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"An individual’s right to limit or prohibit a business or other organization from processing  personal data. ","new_definition":"An individual’s right to limit or prohibit a business or other organization from processing personal data. ","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"16","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/right-to-restriction/"},{"index":"77","term":"Secret Key Encryption","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"“A cryptographic key used with a secret key cryptographic algorithm, uniquely associated with one or more entities and which shall not be made public. The use of the term 'secret' in this context does not imply a classification level; rather the term implies the need to protect the key from disclosure or substitution.” (Federal Information Processing Standards Publication 140-1, Security Requirements for Cryptographic Modules)","new_definition":"A type of encryption requiring the key to remain protected and undisclosed.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"12","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/secret-key"},{"index":"78","term":"Section 5 of the Federal Trade Commission Act","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"Section 5(a) of the F.T.C. Act empowers the agency to enforce against “unfair or deceptive acts or practices in or affecting commerce.” Over the past two decades, the F.T.C. has used this authority extensively to hold businesses to fair and transparent privacy and security standards.","new_definition":"Section 5(a) of the F.T.C. Act empowers the agency to enforce against “unfair or deceptive acts or practices in or affecting commerce.” Over the past two decades, the F.T.C. has used this authority extensively to hold businesses to fair and transparent privacy and security standards.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"45","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/federal-trade-commission-act-section-5-of/"},{"index":"79","term":"Supervisory Authority","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"An independent public authority established by an E.U. member state responsible for monitoring the application of the General Data Protection Regulation.","new_definition":"An independent public authority established by an E.U. member state responsible for monitoring the application of the General Data Protection Regulation.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"21","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/supervisory-authority/"},{"index":"80","term":"Telephone Consumer Protection Act","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"The first laws limiting unsolicited and automated telemarketing for both telephone and fax communications. Most notably the act creates a private right of action for those receiving unsolicited faxes, carrying a $500 fine per violation and any damages sustained because of the fax. The Telephone Consumer Protection Act also gives rule-making authority to the Federal Communications Commission to make further regulations in this area. Among other provisions, the act prevents faxing without consent from the recipient (this requirement was amended by the Junk Fax Prevention Act of 2005 to not include customers with an existing business relationship) and requires companies to create and honor internal do-not-call registries (in 2003 the National Registry was created by the Federal Trade Commission).","new_definition":"The first laws limiting unsolicited and automated telemarketing for both telephone and fax communications. Most notably the act creates a private right of action for those receiving unsolicited faxes, carrying a $500 fine per violation and any damages sustained because of the fax. The Telephone Consumer Protection Act also allows the Federal Communications Commission to make further regulations in this area.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"61","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/telephone-consumer-protection-act-of-1991-amended-in-2003/"},{"index":"81","term":"Third-Party Data","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"Data acquired from a source other than directly from the subject of the data.","new_definition":"Data acquired from a source, instead of directly from the subject of the data.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"14","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/third-party-collection/"},{"index":"82","term":"Tracking Pixel","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"Tracking Pixels","definition":"Also known as a web bug, pixel tag or clear GIF, a web beacon is a clear graphic image (typically one pixel in size) that is delivered through a web browser or HTML e-mail. The web beacon operates as a tag that records an end user’s visit to a particular web page or viewing of a particular e-mail. It is also often used in conjunction with a web cookie and provided as part of a third-party tracking service. Web beacons provide an ability to produce specific profiles of user behavior in combination with web server logs. Common usage scenarios for web beacons include online ad impression counting, file download monitoring, and ad campaign performance management. Web beacons also can report to the sender about which e-mails are read by recipients. Privacy considerations for web beacons are similar to those for cookies. Some sort of notice is important because the clear pixel of a web beacon is quite literally invisible to the end user.","new_definition":"Also known as “clear GIFs” or “pixel tags”, a tracking pixel is typically a one-pixel, transparent image that records when a user has visited a web page or opened an email. It is often used in conjunction with a web cookie. Some sort of notice of use is important because the clear pixel of a web beacon is quite literally invisible to the end user.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"65","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/web-beacon/"},{"index":"83","term":"Transparency","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"Taking appropriate measures to provide any information relating to processing to the data subject in a concise, intelligible and easily accessible form, using clear and plain language.","new_definition":"Taking appropriate measures to provide any information relating to processing to the data subject in a concise, intelligible and easily accessible form, using clear and plain language.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"27","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/transparency/"},{"index":"84","term":"Vendor Management","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"","definition":"Assessment of a third-party vendor for the vendor’s privacy and information security policies, access controls, where the personal information will be held and who has access to it. Security questionnaires, privacy impact assessments and other checklists can be used to assess this risk.","new_definition":"Assessment of a third-party vendor for the vendor’s privacy and information security policies, access controls, where the personal information will be held and who has access to it. Security questionnaires, privacy impact assessments and other checklists can be used to assess this risk.","changed?":"no","wordcount":"43","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/vendor-assessment/"},{"index":"85","term":"Web Beacon","hide_tooltip":"","secondary_terms":"Web Beacons","definition":"Also known as a web bug, pixel tag or clear GIF, a web beacon is a clear graphic image (typically one pixel in size) that is delivered through a web browser or HTML email. The web beacon operates as a tag that records an end user’s visit to a particular web page or viewing of a particular email. It is also often used in conjunction with a web cookie and provided as part of a third-party tracking service. Web beacons provide an ability to produce specific profiles of user behavior in combination with web server logs. Common usage scenarios for web beacons include online ad impression counting, file download monitoring, and ad campaign performance management. Web beacons also can report to the sender which emails are read by recipients. Privacy considerations for web beacons are similar to those for cookies. Some sort of notice is important because the clear pixel of a web beacon is quite literally invisible to the end user.","new_definition":"Also known as “clear GIFs” or “pixel tags,” a web beacon is typically a one-pixel, transparent image that records when a user has visited a web page or opened an email. It is often used in conjunction with a web cookie. Some sort of notice of use is important because the clear pixel of a web beacon is quite literally invisible to the end user.","changed?":"yes","wordcount":"65","url":"https://iapp.org/resources/article/web-beacon/"}]
